The DFT results further clearly indicate that CDs in 5 %CDs-BiO1-xCl provide binding sites for PS to form complexes, while Ov accelerates the transformation of these reactive complexes on CDs into sulfate radicals, which aligns well with the DFT calculations. The calculated adsorption energies of PS at the Bi sites of BiOCl and BiO1-xCl, as well as at the C sites of CDs-BiOCl and CDs-BiO1-xCl, are -1.28, -1.73, -3.61, and -1.52 eV, respectively (Fig. 6
                           ). These values indicate that PS can be efficiently adsorbed onto the surface of the catalysts. In order to gain a deep insight into the transformation of formed complexes in round-the-clock system under visible light irradiation, the thermodynamic feasibility of the reaction pathways for the generation of free radicals was further explored. The results reveal that the formation of PS complexes and subsequent free radical generation at the C site is thermodynamically more favorable than at the Bi site, owing to the lower energy requirement for complex formation at the C site. Specifically, the reaction energy for complex formation between PS and the C site of CDs-BiOCl is 0.08 eV (Fig. 6c and f), which is nearly identical to that of CDs-BiO1-xCl but significantly lower than Bi sites of BiOCl (0.80 eV) and BiO1-xCl (0.78 eV), indicating that the edge C atoms in CDs play a crucial role in the formation of the complexes. However, it is worth noting that Ov plays a crucial role in lowering the energy barrier for the conversion of these complexes into ·SO4
                           -. To further elucidate the interaction between PS and 5 %CDs-BiO1-xCl, the changes in electron density distribution were analyzed. The charge transfer between PS and CDs-BiO1-xCl (0.92 e) is significantly higher than PS and CDs-BiOCl (0.64 e), indicating that Ov enhances electron transfer from the catalyst to PS, thereby facilitating its activation. More importantly, for CDs-BiO1-xCl, the generation of ·SO4⁻ by the complexes at the C site of CDs is spontaneous (-4.31 eV), which is significantly lower than the energy required for ·SO4⁻ generation from surface complexes in CDs-BiOCl (-3.21 eV) (Fig. 6f). Thus, by integrating both experimental and computational findings, the crucial role of C in 5 %CDs-BiO1-xCl in PS activation via the electron transfer pathway, and the promoting effect of Ov in facilitating the conversion of complexes into reactive radicals are effectively illustrated.
